reviews.review_text:
Like a '76 -- slow, sweet and sticky This show reminds me of what I like about '76 -- slow and jazzy. TLEO is particularly nice, but I also like the He's Gone. Pretty funny to hear some calls for Alligator at the beginning of that one -- I don't think they really had that in the rotation in '79, but it was an interesting shout-out :). 

Sound is great on this one -- as always from Charlie Miller. But the Boys are on and the setlist is nice (could do without the From the Heart of Me, but hey, the rest is music to my ears :) ).

Jack-a-roe The mama tried, jack a roe, and Bertha are fabulous takes, extending beyond normal capacity, Garcia truly shining at his very best...

A fine recording, fullest and cleanest from the list..

~ Peggyo

no rythm devil's No drums and space at this show odd to say the least.Still a good show top to bottom. That said though with all of the other shows during this tour is kinda middle of the road.  Sounds great though

Reliving the days Suddenly...or maybe not so...after watching Long Strange Trip, and feeling sad... really sad about how this great scene dwindled into a hot mess, been going back to listen to the shows I attended. This one was one of my first while I was early in HS, and while I was sneaking away from private school to see shows during the '77-78 run of great shows, I had no idea what I was seeing in the making.  Along comes '79, just before my 17 birthday, and remember the snow and cold, blizzards that the tour was being chased by.  This show really warmed things up...  Listening to it, it was a good, solid show from that tour... really seemed to kick into gear with FOTD, on through what was normally shows that were slow to get out of gate... wrapped up with a sweet, rockin' Deal. Donna's voice gets a lot of criticism for "wailing" out of tune, though I've been told that the monitors on stage were so loud, it was hard for her to really keep her pitch in synch. This show the sound seemed pretty dialed in and her vocal was really there. Second set is totally solid from top to bottom, and Donna shines on FTHOM with the band really in the groove on this musically funkily-noted tune.  Really some stellar moments (SOF>He's>Truckin;) in this show, and I've been digging Phil's booming base lines, and really hearing how Bobby plays some intricate notes to keep it all held down with the drummers. Worth having this show in your collection.

I Stumbled on it by accident...Glad I Did So, I was looking for a show from 79 to listen to and I incorrectly read somewhere that this was Keith and Donna's last show. Being from Providence, RI I went to the archive and prompted put the show on. I started reading the reviews and no where did it mention being Keith and Donna's last show. But at this point I was committed. If I put a show on, it's like an OCD thing with me, but I have to listen to the whole show. 
Anyhow, after researching and finding out this is NOT Keith and Donna's last show (I will be listening to that immediately after this), I started listening to this show. I'm glad I did. I must say that it isn't incredible, or outstanding in anyway, but it is a Solid Grateful Dead Show. I know I mentioned above that I am from Providence, and maybe that makes me a little biased, but I have found that the shows from Rhode Island never disappoint. Look at the show from 74 that became a Dick's Pick. That has to have the jazziest China ever. Amd the shows from 1987 (some of my first shows), they were just on fire. I'm not sure what it is about the energy in Providence but whatever it is the boys seem to feed off of it, and provide solid shows. So, if you were considering listening to this show, but you weren't sure....do yourself a favor a listen

Its a nice mellow show with a good set of songs in each set.

At 16 this may or may not be my first show?... Still trying to figure out if this or Nov 4, 79 was my first hometown show when I was 16. If anyone recalls either of these 79 shows it was the one where this naked hippie chick leapt from the front row barrier to the edge of stage during intermission landing hard on her shins and then got up disoriented and gave everyone a peace sign before four roadies came out and carried her off stage. Unfortunately I don't have the ticket stub so can't be sure so if anyone remembers either of these shows I'd love to narrow it down to which one was officially my first show. You can add your response as a review here or email me at theeleven at live dot com Thanks all!
